newCaseBoxplotHeaderHTML.html: How to interpret these charts: The bar across the middle of the box gives the median of all states on that date. Half the states fall within the box, a quarter above it and a quarter below it. Dots in a horizontal line near the top of the graph are not real data, but mean there is a data point at that level or higher (if the graph were scaled to show everything, the interesting part of the graph would be all squished at the bottom)

testGrowthHeaderHTML.html:
Changes in Amount of Testing

The data used for this tab is not updated as regularly as the data for cases and mortality, and is not always reliable. Uneven updates can result in numbers which change the scale so much that the resulting chart is unreadable. To prevent that, these graphs do not display data which is far outside the range of the bulk of the data. Dots along the top or bottom of the chart are not real data.

The amount of testing should generally not be decreasing.

A downward sloping trend line is not necessarily a problem. It just means that the amount of testing is not growing as fast as it used to be. So long as the growth rate is above 0 the number of tests is increasing.

testResultsHeaderHTML.html:
Changes in Test Results

A decreasing percentage of positive tests is good; it means that tests are becoming more widely available.

Think of the extreme case: if everyone were tested, and 0 percent of tests were positive, the epidemic would be over.

vaccHeaderHTML.html:
Vaccinations, People Fully Vaccinated

Vaccination data is shown by percent of state or of US as a whole.

Highest People Fully Vaccinated rate: Puerto Rico with 64.9 percent

Next highest rate: Massachusetts with 62.5 percent

Lowest People Fully Vaccinated rate: Alabama with 38.6 percent

Next lowest rate: Louisiana with 41.3 percent

Note that 'Total Doses' will be above 100% when close to 50% of the population has had a second dose!
